ChangedDaily !!bV77eH2fdKV Fri 06 Aug 2021 01:10:05 No.40702901 Report
Quoted By: >>40703312
I mean no ill will towards Smiling, I'm a fan of some of his other work. He's a great dude. I have problems with 'Violence.'
The dialogue is fine on its own, revenge is a strong enough motive for a piece like this. Some of it feels melodramatic as we lack any real connections to the combatants, but with a little more attachment, some of these lines would probably hit much harder than they do.
Just calling them armored man and unarmored man is unacceptable because it distracts the reader (Similar names/titles are easy to confuse) and harms the flow. Even if you wanted to keep the characters anonymous you could given them more distinct titles. Armored man could have been 'the knight', 'the swordsman' or 'the paladin', and unarmored man could just as easily become 'the renegade' or 'the brigand.'
Speaking of flow, it's been brought up before but this isn't how you do a fight scene. There is WAY too much description for individual movements, description. When combined with some pretty egregious run-on sentences, it makes the scene incredibly difficult to follow.
This is one sentence:
>The unarmored man throws another right-handed strike, but this time the armored man parries by slicing his clawed index finger down the middle, splitting the claw, then the tough mammalian bone, through the soft tendons and prying apart the gaps of the bones in his hand, turning the unarmored mans' own strength against him, in less than a blink of an eye the blade of the armored man has found itself through the arm of the unarmored man, having split his radius away from his ulna, and soon forcing its way past the elbow, the lower half of the unarmored man's arm begins to fall away from his body, and the far weaker strike doesn't even turn the armored man's helmeted head.
It's alot of words to say 'He retaliates by slicing down the brigand's finger, completely splitting his foe's lower arm between the bones in a fraction of a second.' There's a better compromise somewhere.
